<section xml:id="sec52-DefiniteIntegral" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The Definite Integral</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this section, we will formalize the three approximation methods and investigate a new concept called <term>definite integral</term>. 
      We will explore some basic properties of definite integrals. 
    </p>

    <objectives>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          After this section, students will be able to:
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            understand the concept of Riemann sum, including the construction of rectangles using the given partition and sample points. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            understand the concept of definite integrals, including each component of it and its meaning. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            evaluate basic definite integrals using either geometry or basic formulas. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            apply linearity and basic properties to break apart and evaluate definite integral. 
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>
    
  </introduction>

  <investigation>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Recall the big goal in <xref ref="sec51-ApproximatingArea"/> is to compute the area under the curve. 
        Let's see if we can come up with some basic formulas we can use directly. 
      </p>

      <p>
        Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be positive real numbers such that <m>a &lt; b</m>. 
        Find the area of the following function over the indicated interval. 
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <task>
      <p>
        <m>f(x) = K</m> over <m>[a,b]</m> for any positive real number <m>K</m>. 
      </p>

      <hint>
        <p>
          Graph it out! Label the region of interest! What shape is it? 
        </p>
      </hint>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Let's first graph the function and highlight the region of interest. 
        </p>

        <figure>
          <caption>The graph of <m>y = K</m> with the region under the curve on <m>[a,b]</m> shaded.</caption>
          <image width="50%">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                  axis lines=middle,
                  xmin=0, xmax=4.5,
                  ymin=0, ymax=3.5,
                  xtick={1,4},
                  xticklabels={$a$,$b$},
                  ytick={2},
                  yticklabels={$K$},
                  samples=200
                ]
                  % --- Shaded region
                  \addplot [
                    domain=1:4,
                    samples=2,
                    fill=green!30,
                    draw=none
                  ] {2} \closedcycle;

                  % --- Function line
                  \addplot [thick, blue] {2};

                  % --- Dashed boundaries at x=a and x=b
                  \addplot[dashed] coordinates {(1,0) (1,2)};
